theorem
(s is  summable implies (for n holds ( Sum s ) = ( ( ( Partial_Sums s ) . n ) + ( Sum ( s ^\ ( n + 1 ) ) ) )))
proof
defpred X[ (Element of ( NAT )) ]
 means
( Sum s ) = ( ( ( Partial_Sums s ) . $1 ) + ( Sum ( s ^\ ( $1 + 1 ) ) ) );
assume A1: s is  summable;
A2: (for n holds (X[ n ] implies X[ ( n + 1 ) ]))
proof
let n;
assume A3: ( Sum s ) = ( ( ( Partial_Sums s ) . n ) + ( Sum ( s ^\ ( n + 1 ) ) ) );
reconsider s1 = ( ( NAT ) --> ( ( s ^\ ( n + 1 ) ) . ( 0 ) ) ) as Real_Sequence;
(for k holds ( s1 . k ) = ( ( s ^\ ( n + 1 ) ) . ( 0 ) )) by FUNCOP_1:7;
then A4: ( Partial_Sums ( ( s ^\ ( n + 1 ) ) ^\ 1 ) ) = ( ( ( Partial_Sums ( s ^\ ( n + 1 ) ) ) ^\ 1 ) - s1 ) by CKB17:1;
( s ^\ ( n + 1 ) ) is  summable by A1,CKB18:1;
then A5: ( Partial_Sums ( s ^\ ( n + 1 ) ) ) is  convergent by CKB7:def 1;
( lim ( Partial_Sums ( s ^\ ( ( n + 1 ) + 1 ) ) ) ) = ( lim ( Partial_Sums ( ( s ^\ ( n + 1 ) ) ^\ 1 ) ) ) by NAT_1:48
.= ( ( lim ( ( Partial_Sums ( s ^\ ( n + 1 ) ) ) ^\ 1 ) ) - ( lim s1 ) ) by A5,A4,SEQ_2:12
.= ( ( lim ( Partial_Sums ( s ^\ ( n + 1 ) ) ) ) - ( lim s1 ) ) by A5,SEQ_4:20
.= ( ( Sum ( s ^\ ( n + 1 ) ) ) - ( s1 . ( 0 ) ) ) by SEQ_4:26
.= ( ( Sum ( s ^\ ( n + 1 ) ) ) - ( ( s ^\ ( n + 1 ) ) . ( 0 ) ) ) by FUNCOP_1:7;
then ( Sum ( s ^\ ( ( n + 1 ) + 1 ) ) ) = ( ( Sum s ) - ( ( ( Partial_Sums s ) . n ) + ( ( s ^\ ( n + 1 ) ) . ( 0 ) ) ) ) by A3
.= ( ( Sum s ) - ( ( ( Partial_Sums s ) . n ) + ( s . ( ( 0 ) + ( n + 1 ) ) ) ) ) by NAT_1:def 3
.= ( ( Sum s ) - ( ( Partial_Sums s ) . ( n + 1 ) ) ) by CKB6:def 1;
hence thesis;
end;
A6: X[ ( 0 ) ]
proof
